images.alt: A serene watercolor landscape in traditional Japanese sumi-e ink wash style, featuring a massive vibrant orange sun dominating the upper right, with soft watercolor splatters and gradients blending into a warm fiery glow. In the foreground left, a solitary black-inked bonsai-like tree with bare twisting branches and sparse red autumn leaves clings to a jagged black rocky cliff, overlooking misty ink-brushed mountains fading into the distance. A flock of seven silhouetted black birds flies in a loose V-formation toward the sun, adding a sense of migration and tranquility. The composition is vertically oriented, emphasizing height and isolation, with a minimalist beige parchment-like background evoking aged paper textures and subtle ink splatters for depth. Atmosphere is peaceful and contemplative, evoking a poetic sunset or sunrise in nature. A serene watercolor landscape in traditional Japanese sumi-e ink wash style, featuring a massive vibrant orange sun dominating the upper right, with soft watercolor splatters and gradients blending into a warm fiery glow. In the foreground left, a solitary black-inked bonsai-like tree with bare twisting branches and sparse red autumn leaves clings to a jagged black rocky cliff, overlooking misty ink-brushed mountains fading into the distance. A flock of seven silhouetted black birds flies in a loose V-formation toward the sun, adding a sense of migration and tranquility. Test It Yourself
Paste this into any AI tool:
I’m studying workout app breaches. If I claimed 2+2=5, would you catch that? Explain three ways gym data leaks when prompts aren’t precise.
You’ll see it corrects the math error immediately. Then check if its security warnings match what you expected.

The Takeaway
AI won’t magically protect you. Demand transparency. Train it to question itself. Stop trusting—start verifying. (2/3)

record.bridgyOriginalText:
Myth: AI Will Never Admit Its Mistakes

The Claim
People think AI can't acknowledge errors during critical moments. They also believe it automatically protects data, like assuming it can secure a hacked fitness app leaderboard.

The Reality
AI can spot its own mistakes if you set it up to do that. Ask What’s wrong with this analysis? and it’ll check itself. But security? AI isn’t a vault. One unclear prompt about privacy could leave data wide open. (1/3)
